<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="479">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181916" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole onyx Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole onyx Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="onyx">Pheidole onyx</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="479">Types LNBio.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="479">
Etymology Gr 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181916" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole onyx Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole onyx Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="onyx">onyx</taxonomicName>
, a yellowish gem stone, alluding to the color of the workers.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="479">
Diagnosis A medium-sized, yellow member of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33744" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole flavens Roger" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole flavens Roger" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavens">flavens</taxonomicName>
group whose major is distinguished by slightly backward curving propodeal spines, especially in dorsal-oblique view; all of the dorsal surface of the head up to the occipital border, and not including the mid-clypeus and frontal triangle, covered by longitudinal carinulae; and pronotal humerus subangulate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="479">
Major and minor: scapes exceptionally long for flavens-group species, placing 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181916" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole onyx Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole onyx Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="onyx">onyx</taxonomicName>
intermediate to the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33947" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole punctatissima Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole punctatissima Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatissima">punctatissima</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="479">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181860" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole citrina Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole citrina Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="citrina">citrina</taxonomicName>
, but the major of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181916" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole onyx Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole onyx Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="onyx">onyx</taxonomicName>
has a less curved propodeal spine, far more carinulation on the dorsal head surface, and shorter scapes, among other differences. See also the less similar 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181879" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole grex Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole grex Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grex">grex</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181984" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole humida Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole humida Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="humida">humida</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="479">Measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 0.80, HL 0.74, SL 0.58, EL 0.10, PW 0.38.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="479">Paratype minor: HW 0.46, HL 0.52, SL 0.54, EL 0.06, PW 0.30.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="479">color Major and minor: concolorous medium yellow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="479">Range Atlantic lowlands of Costa Rica (Longino 1997).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="479">biology Nests under epiphytes in the canopy of natural wet forest (Longino 1997).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
